#compdef totp-ssh-fluxer
# ============================================================================
# totp-ssh-fluxer - SSH port fluxer using TOTP (Go, no-license / source-open)
#
# Author : Ben Cox (benjojo)
# Upstream: https://github.com/benjojo/totp-ssh-fluxer
#
# totp-ssh-fluxer takes the sshd "change to non-standard port" form
# of security-through-obscurity to its logical extreme: instead of
# picking one obscure port, it rotates the active SSH port every
# 30 seconds based on a TOTP secret shared between the server and
# the operator's authenticator app. The daemon loops:
#
#   1. Generate a TOTP code from the shared secret
#   2. Use the leading digits as the port number (clamped <= 65535)
#   3. Add an iptables PREROUTING NAT rule redirecting that port
#      to the real sshd port (22)
#   4. Wait 30 seconds, remove the rule, repeat
#
# Established connections survive port rotation because PREROUTING
# only affects new SYN packets - already-established connections
# stay in the conntrack table and continue to use their original
# port. The operator's phone shows the current "SSH port-of-the-
# moment" via any generic TOTP authenticator app (Aegis / Authy /
# Google Authenticator / 1Password / Bitwarden Authenticator).
#
# The TOTP lane is built on `github.com/pquerna/otp` (declared at
# upstream go.mod HEAD), the canonical Go TOTP / HOTP library by
# Paul Querna (github.com/pquerna/otp, 2900+ stars). The library
# implements RFC 6238 (TOTP) layered on RFC 4226 (HOTP) end-to-
# end: HMAC-SHA1/SHA256/SHA512 modes, 6-8 digit truncation, the
# `otpauth://` URI parser + emitter, Google-Authenticator-
# compatible QR code generation, and the `Key` / `Generate` /
# `Validate` API surface used by every Go web framework's MFA
# middleware. Verbatim from upstream `main.go`:
#
#     import (
#         "github.com/pquerna/otp"
#         "github.com/pquerna/otp/totp"
#     )
#
#     otpkey, _ := otp.NewKeyFromURL(token)
#     code, _ := totp.GenerateCode(otpkey.Secret(), time.Now())
#     port, _ := strconv.ParseInt(code[:5], 10, 64)
#     ...
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 218 :: TOTP (RFC 6238 Time-based One-Time Password Algorithm)
# Round 1353 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 218
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : storyfeet/totp-lite + constantoine/totp-rs   [R1352 _totp]
#   Go      : pquerna/otp                                  [R1353 THIS FILE]
#   TS/Node : yeojz/otplib                                 [R1354 closing]
#
# pquerna/otp has the structurally distinctive position of being
# both an HOTP + TOTP + URI library AND a QR code emitter in a
# single import path - the URI -> Key -> QR PNG pipeline is the
# canonical "enroll a TOTP for a new user" flow, and pquerna's
# library is the Go solution end-to-end. Rust + Node lanes
# typically separate the algorithm library (totp-rs / otplib)
# from the QR generator (qrcode-rust / node-qrcode at Axis 199).
#
# totp-ssh-fluxer is the canonical "creative misuse of TOTP"
# pattern - using TOTP as a covert side-channel for something
# other than user-facing MFA codes. Same flavor as input-method-
# as-LSP (Axis 216 _rime_ls) and Chinese-IME-via-completion: the
# spec is generic enough to encompass workloads the original
# authors never anticipated.
# ============================================================================

_totp-ssh-fluxer() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '-keypath[unix path to the TOTP URI key file (default /etc/ssh-flux-key)]:file:_files' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]'
}

_totp-ssh-fluxer "$@"
